# PR Sizing

## 1. Purpose

PRs are reviewed faster, regress less often, and roll back cleaner when they are small. zedos enforces explicit limits on diff size and the surface area touched.

This rule complements:

- `.cursor/rules/70-execution-bridge.mdc` — every PR maps to an Implementation Plan + User Story
- `.cursor/commands/split.md` — the route for breaking up oversized work
- `.cursor/checkers/pr-readiness-checker.md` — the gate that enforces these limits

---

## 2. Default limits

A PR is considered **standard size** when **all** of:

| Metric | Limit | Rationale |
|---|---|---|
| Net lines changed (added + removed) | ≤ 400 | Reviewer fatigue starts here |
| Files touched | ≤ 15 | Cross-cutting changes are often refactors hiding inside features |
| Hexagonal layers touched | ≤ 3 | A PR touching every layer is usually two PRs in a trench coat |
| Packages touched (post-migration) | ≤ 3 | Same reasoning |
| Test files touched | ≤ 5 | A PR with 10 new test files probably contains two features |
| Schema migrations | ≤ 1 | One logical schema change per PR |
| Commits | ≤ 10 (squash-eligible) | More commits than that needs a rebase first |

A PR within all limits is **standard size** and follows the standard review SLA. A PR that exceeds any one limit is **oversized** and routes through `/split` before review.

## 3. Exemptions (must be declared)

A PR may exceed these limits when it is:

- **Mechanical refactor** — a tool-driven rename, codemod, or formatting pass. Must declare `mechanical-refactor` in the PR title prefix and link the codemod source.
- **Generated code update** — schema regeneration, OpenAPI client regen, etc. Must declare `generated` in the title prefix and link the generator command.
- **Pure migration step** — a numbered phase in `docs/retro/zedos-monorepo-retro.md` (e.g. P0.3 — moving `zedos/nextjs_space/` to `apps/web/`). Must reference the phase ID.
- **Single-commit revert** — the inverse of a recent merge. Must link the original PR.

No other exemptions. "It's all related" is not a category. If reviewers disagree on the categorization, the PR splits.

## 4. Stacked PR pattern

When work is genuinely sequential (foundation → consumer), prefer **stacked PRs**:

```
main
└── feature/credits-ledger-foundation        (PR #N)
    └── feature/credits-purchase-flow        (PR #N+1, base = PR #N)
        └── feature/credits-purchase-ui      (PR #N+2, base = PR #N+1)
```

Each PR in the stack independently passes the size limits. The `/split` command produces the stack; `/babysit` keeps each layer green.

## 5. PR description must include

Every PR description names its lineage:

```md
## Summary
<1–3 sentences: what changed and why>

## Linked artifacts
- Scope Slice: docs/product/scope-slices/<fa>--<slice>.md
- User Story: docs/execution/user-stories/<fa>--<slice>--<story>.md
- Implementation Plan: docs/execution/plans/<...>.plan.md
- Decision references: PD-NNN (if any)

## Test plan
- [ ] Unit tests added/updated
- [ ] Integration tests added/updated (if persistence / contracts touched)
- [ ] E2E tests added (if a new user-facing journey ships)
- [ ] Manual verification (steps)

## Out of scope (deliberate)
- <thing not in this PR but adjacent>
```

`pr-readiness-checker.md` refuses to open a PR missing these sections.

## 6. Hard rules

1. PRs that exceed §2 limits without a declared §3 exemption do not open. `/split` runs first.
2. Mixed-purpose PRs (refactor + new feature in the same diff) split. The "while I was there" rule fragments review.
3. Schema migrations ship in PRs that **only** modify schema + generated code + minimal adapter wiring. Application logic that depends on the new schema ships in a follow-up.
4. Cross-package refactors (`packages/*`) run via `/split` to produce one PR per package.
5. Reverts are their own PR — never bundled with new work.

## 7. Enforced by

| Mechanism | Enforces |
|---|---|
| `.cursor/checkers/pr-readiness-checker.md` | §2 limits, §5 description requirements |
| `.cursor/commands/split.md` | §3 exemptions, §4 stacked PR construction |
| `.cursor/agents/execution/reviewer.md` | §6 hard rules at review time |
| `.cursor/hooks/pre-pr.sh` | §2 limits before allowing PR creation |
